  <ns3227:title xmlns:ns3227="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">The Java API for XML-based Remote Procedure Call (JAX-RPC)</ns3227:title>
  <ns3228:para xmlns:ns3228="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    JAX-RPC, the <ns3229:emphasis xmlns:ns3229="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java API for XML-based Remote Procedure Calls</ns3229:emphasis>
    is effectively an implementation of a Web-Services/SOAP based ORB (Object
    Request Broker). It facilitates the simple generation of web services servers
    and clients, taking over the responsibilities of connecting clients to servers, 
    marshalling/demarshalling SOAP based service requests.
  </ns3228:para>
  <!-- TODO: This is no longer relevant with the advant of JAX-WS -->
  <!--para>
    In JAX-RPC a web service end-point is usually a servlet which is generated by JAX-RPC.
    This servlet acts as the server which demarshalls the SOAP-based service request and
    delegates the realization of that service request to a user developed servant class which
    is a straight-forward java class.
    </para-->
  <ns3230:para xmlns:ns3230="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    From Java EE version 5 onwards, the newly-introduced <ns3231:literal xmlns:ns3231="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">JAX-WS</ns3231:literal> will replace
    JAX-RPC.
  </ns3230:para>
  
